  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and frameworks aimed at preventing money laundering:\n\n1. Financial Action Task Force (FATF)\n- Sets global standards for combating money laundering\n- Provides recommendations for national legal and regulatory systems\n\n2. United Nations Conventions\n- UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime\n- UN Convention against Corruption\n\n3. OECD Anti-Bribery Convention\n- Addresses international financial crimes\n\n4. Basel Committee on Banking Supervision\n- Provides guidelines for banks to prevent money laundering\n\n5. Individual Country Regulations\n- Most countries have their own anti-money laundering (AML) laws\n- Examples include the U.S. Bank Secrecy Act and EU Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n\n6. International Monetary Fund (IMF) Guidelines\n- Provides recommendations and assistance to countries in developing AML strategies\n\nThese frameworks require financial institutions to:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Implement compliance programs\n\nWhile these are not always directly enforceable, they create international standards and expectations for combating financial crimes.",
